column1: For any seven consecutive day period between 9 October 2020 and 15 June 2021, will there be fewer than 50,000 combined total confirmed new cases of COVID-19 in the United States?
column6: ['Health']

This question could possibly close tomorrow on 12 June 2021 (if the GJO wanted), since the last possible moving 7d window (9 June through 15 June) will have accumulated more than 50k new cases already. It is notable that Florida, which used to report about 2k new cases per day, appears to be not even included in the latest reports, since there seems to be a major testing breakdown from 06 June 2021.
50K per week is not possible since right now it is at 13K or around that number per day. With this rate, 50K will be reached in 4-5 days.

50k per week is 7.1k per day. WHO still reporting around 13k per day. Can go up and down in a daily basis quite alot, but it has to halve and rates are slightly increasing. So for that to happen in the next week seems a bit difficult.
1% ~ possibility of error
Going the wrong way now. Sadly, it ain't gonna happen.

It's over. Preview of today's cases: approx 16,126. Cases are now increasing a bit and moving farther from a trend line than they have since April 14. Even if the decline continues, it can't be steep enough in time for this question. It's been fun, @JonathanMann, @CJH, @cafebedouin, @Okanaganopolis! Thanks for the discussions and for trying to save me from myself. :)
Looks like cases may have leveled off a bit. Also could just be a reporting thing. But does seem less likely after the weekend. -15.

6 June was below the required average (7143) with 6408 according to worldometers. But it was a sunday, usually by far the lowest number of a week. We would need a miracle to have similar numbers monday-friday this week, and those will be included in the last possible 7-day period for this question. Going all in.
I can't reason enough time.
Florida alone appears to have had approx. 12k new cases in the first six days of June, Texas has had ~9.5k new cases.

50,000 new cases per week equates to 7143 new cases per day, or about 21.5 new cases per million population (2.15 new cases per 100k population). See https://covidactnow.org/?s=1898818 for new cases per 100k population and for the reinfection rates for all 50 states plus DC.
Going down slightly after thinking about my full probability distribution for a separate question

I still think <50k is possible, but it would be very tight. Update 6/6: preview of June 6 cases: approx 5285. The next couple days will likely show where this is going, which almost everyone but me is very certain is not <50k. I recognize that I will probably have a terrible Brier score on this, but this is my honest prediction.
1. I expect one thing and the trend drops further. 2. Risk averse forecast.
h/t @elifland
50k per week is 7.1k per day. Down to 14k per day, but only 10 days to go to halve rate, and that is not the rate of decline seen. Also end may holiday yet to manifest in cases.
Combined total cases - read the question wrong
It is already 5 June and since trend is already down but have not looked at the numbers (just peeked) but yes

Preview of June 4 cases: approx 17458. The previously linear decline is slowing slightly. Current forecast June 11 for <50k/week by WHO data, assuming WHO cases are a conservative 10% less than jhu cases. I anticipate this date will continue to shift later as time goes on; the outcome will be close, and we might not see <50k in the forecast period.

The average Rt for the 50 states + DC fell to 0.775 on June 1, and has since risen to 0.789. See https://covidactnow.org/?s=1893813, and find the average of the "Infection Rate" column. The oscillating pattern with a minimum mid-week and a maximum over the weekend has continued. But the overall trend since April 20 has been down. A 6.4% per day decline will have to be sustained to get the number of new infections below 50k/wk by June 15. That's only a little faster than the current rate of decrease. The rate could be accelerating downward, but I would note that the holiday weekend caused a glitch in the curve that obscures the trend.

Cases dropped by 55,000 in the last week, if the same were to happen over the next week it would be pretty close with 4 days to spare. That's based on Our World in Data though, which looks like it might have different numbers from WHO. But this is looking a lot more plausible than I would have guessed. Going up for now.
A small few quants in this group are rising fast in their bets. I'm gonna "hedge" up from the crowd. however I believe at a certain number, it just won't drop "below".

I think we'll likely be under 50k/week according to jhu data by around June 10-13, and according to WHO data by around June 9-12. My line predicts WHO data will be under 50k/week by June 8, but I'm allowing a few more days for the decline to slow. We may just squeak in under 50k, but I think it's likely we'll get there before June 15. (I note that the question closes with June 14 data.) PS I do note that I am perhaps the only one around who is forecasting "yes" so high.

I shouldn't forget that the WHO numbers are lower than other numbers. WHO data for the week ending May 24 are 11.6% lower than JHU data, and 16.0% lower for the week ending May 17. A linear forecast has been holding really well for the 7-day average for the past 50 days, although it's possible that the curve has started to turn. (A few days ago, I was worried that the curve might be turning upward, but that seems not to be happening, at least.) Right now, forecasting a conservative 10% undercount by WHO, the WHO should register fewer than 50k cases/week by June 8; that date may well get pushed out a few days, though.

I think it's gonna be a matter of days or weeks but the trends say no in terms of the question's criteria. My estimate is aided by my analysis on this question that just opened: https://www.gjopen.com/questions/2025-how-many-confirmed-cases-of-covid-19-in-the-us-will-be-reported-for-the-week-ending-3-july-2021.

Moving up to 50:50. As discussed in previous comments, a linear forecast fits the past now 49 days of 7-day average cases/day really well and slightly better than an exponential fit. At some point, the curve will turn towards zero, and it's possible that this turn has started. The holiday weekend has obscured trends, but hopefully we will know better what is going on once we have data from June 2 or 3. I choose to base my guess about where the curve will bend based on the example of Israel; if it occurred here at the same case load as in Israel, adjusted for population, it would be at ~11k cases/day. There are various reasons to think it would be different in the US (e.g., slightly higher vaccination rate in Israel would make Israel's numbers lower; later time in spring would make US numbers lower), but it's a start. We will likely be at ~11k/day by June 5 or 6. If cases continue falling linearly past that point, we'll see 50k/week by around June 9 or 10. But it's also possible that there will be an uptick in cases because fewer people are wearing masks or variants are spreading more. We'll soon know.

The US is probably going to miss the target value of this question by a week or so. Still needs a decline of ~14k/day. The past few weeks the decay averaged 1k/day per day, which with 14 days remaining would indicate success, but we should now start seeing pockets of the US where Covid is already eradicated and pockets where there is still a sufficient distribution to sustain community transmission. This will reduce the rate of decline (also: no idea why the case numbers no longer follow exponential growth/decline models) and probably make us miss the deadline for this question.
A lot of chaos with testing and reporting because of the holiday weekend, but I am cautiously optimistic.

If the increase of the few days leading up to the holiday weekend were transient, then I think it's likely we'll see <50k cases in the 2nd week of June. Cases reported for yesterday (jhu data) were 52% of cases 1 week before. Cases reported for the day before were 61% of the week before. But with likely reduced testing and reporting over the holiday weekend, it's hard to know what's really going on right now. Plus, we'll likely see a rebound in reported cases on June 1 and possibly a bit on June 2. Hopefully testing and reporting will settle down by June 2 or 3.
Continued declining trend in https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/us/ makes this seem plausible
back with crowd

Maintaining 0%. I feel like stating the obvious this morning: the US won’t fall below 50k/week in June because vaccines don’t protect the unvaccinated. The subset of US citizens who remain unvaccinated correlates strongly to the subset who refuse to wear masks and social distance. COVID rates among this group have not declined at all since January. There is still plenty of (obstinate, selfish, misguided) tinder for the virus to burn through. Here’s an analysis from the Washington Post: https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/interactive/2021/covid-rates-unvaccinated-people/?itid=hp_pandemic%20test.

As per my previous comment, we would need to see a pretty steep acceleration in the *rate* of declining cases in order for this question to resolve as true. I created a chart mapping the past trajectory and various outcomes based on a 15%,20%,25%, and 30% rate of decline. I'm expecting the outcome to fall somewhere between the 15% and the 25% projections, but I'll update if any of the weekly numbers along the way resolve higher than expected. Here is the chart: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jonathanmann/gjopen/master/weekly_covid_cases/weekly_covid_cases.png I'm using the data from the WHO dashboard linked in the question description: https://covid19.who.int/region/amro/country/us
Feels unlikely but possible
The decline of the past month and a half may be starting to drift from linear. I'll move to the crowd forecast until it's clear which way things are going.
A two week halving resolves this question positively, but it still seems fairly unlikely. Going up slightly 12% -> 15%

I think the decline in cases would likely continue to well under 50k/week in the forecast period, except that there may now be a new upturn in cases. Is this due to the spread of variants and/or people not wearing masks indoors?

Florida, Colorado, Michigan and probably some other states (NY, NJ, PA) with a rather large scope of premature reopenings could be crucial. CDC's idiotic waiver of masking mandate for vaccinated will protract breakthrough infections. Variants of Concern, B.1.351 and the newly declared VoC B.1.617.2 are still on the table, they are less likely to be inhibited by at least some vaccines, and will thus protract breakthrough infections and new outbreaks. A dozen of states still have a test positivity rate of >5% Two dozens of states still have a high or very high level of community transmission. And, with the relatively low positity rates in the 75% of the states, the number of tests currently is inappropriately low compared to what it should be to become aware of outbreaks early, and will be forced up, once severe outbreaks will occur (perhaps in CA next). In all, the current figures are likely to understate the risk of higher transmission levels; 7-day new cases are unlikely to fall below 70,000 before 01 July 2021, if not longer...

The decline only has to drop by 7.7% and it'll reach target, on average. However, there is still risk about the raw daily counts that is going to be used. I think if we used the average it may be more likely to reach target since it is less noisy than taking the raw daily counts.

Decreasing slightly for passage of time. Weekly cases would need to decline by closer to ~40% per week for this question to resolve as a 'Yes'. Seems unlikely given the weekly declines have been roughly half of that (i.e., ~20%) the past few weeks, but exponential dynamics are tricky. We will likely see an acceleration in declines as vaccinations continue to tick up, but unclear if it will happen quickly enough to impact this question.

New infections are going down fast, just not fast enough to reach 50k/wk. Reducing odds from 7% to 3%.

I tried to use this https://viz.covid19forecasthub.org/ to estimate where it would be. It seems that around closing time, the 7-day moving average of daily cases in the US will be about half its value now—not enough to get to the resolution criteria, I suppose.

The average Rt for the 50 states + DC has fallen to 0.85, which is about where it was two months ago. If it had stayed down this question would already be over. Instead it rose to 1.05 in early April. With only four weeks left until June 15 we would need to see a 5% decrease every day for the next month. It's not impossible, but seems unlikely given the many places where vaccination rates are low. NJ shows what can happen when herd immunity is approached. New infections have fallen off a cliff, with Rt = 0.47. Things could change (again), but if the current trend continues we will reach the 50k/week level before July 4th. I'll keep the odds at 14 to one for a YES answer.
I'm seeing a close call on the horizon. Keeping tabs on that trend line and wary that numbers vary depending on source.
h/t @yagudin - raising my estimate slightly; there's more uncertainty here than I first thought.
With current nearly linear declines, my lowest forecast for the week is just over 50k. Update 5/20: Current forecast 57k. Will likely end up slightly higher.

Recent peak was just under half a million 14th April. Need about a 5% drop every day from now to get there. by 15th June. Average has been about -2.36% and only 1 in 30 days has got close. So that would suggest a probability much less than 3%.

Judging from the small number of updates posted for this question the crowd is very confident of the outcome. The crowd is almost certainly right, having figured it out way before me. I was way too optimistic. But I continue to follow the numbers. While binary questions have an appealing simplicity, it would be interesting to watch the forecasts evolve for a multi-bin question. Possible bins: "On or before June 15," "June 16 through July 15," "July 16 through August 15," and "After August 15."

Dropping to slightly above the crows as the US vaccination speed peaked in mid April. There is no chance, that the epidemic situation will be well enough in order to sustain <50k cases/7days. The remaining option is a refusal to count new cases, which should not happen within the next 6 weeks. I'm staying above the crowd mainly out of stubbornness, but the chance for a yes resolution is realistically gone

Still I think the crowd is a little bit too pessimistic here. My unweighted estimate is probably about 15%.

Chile has vaccinated a larger portion of its population than the US (https://ourworldindata.org/covid-vaccinations?country=), but they have nearly double the infection rate (https://ourworldindata.org/covid-cases). Once they started vaccinating they thought they no longer needed social distancing. They were wrong, and the US is following their lead. We in the US are fortunate to have a more effective vaccine, but we are far from herd immunity. And the clock is running down on this question -- only nine weeks left.

" 'Two factors, however, can slow or even reverse the declines that have begun,' the IHME team said. The first factor is the spread of the B.1.1.7 variant, which was first identified in the UK and experts warned could become the dominant strain in the US by spring. Data from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention shows more than 980 cases of the variant have so far been detected across 37 states. The second factor, according to the IHME team, is 'increased behaviors that favor COVID-19 transmission.' 'Transmission has been contained over the winter through mask wearing, decreased mobility, and avoidance of high-risk settings such as indoor dining,' the team said. 'As daily case counts decline and vaccination increases, behaviors are likely to change towards increased risk of transmission.'

Since peaking in mid-January new infections have fallen steadily at a rate of about two and a half to three percent per day. Plotted on a logarithmic graph it's a fairly straight line. Extrapolating the line gets us below 50k/week in late May. I believe the decline will continue for at least another month, or maybe two. In six weeks we'll be at 250k/week, which matches the lows reached around Labor Day 2020. That's where things could go haywire.
The numbers are heading in the right direction.

21 weeks remaining with a 1.1 million case tally this last week. Current who data has us the last 3 weeks decreasing at 12 and 20%, 20%respectively. The current 7-day average of cases in the U.S. is about ~200,000/day [1]. This amounts to ~1,400,000 total cases in the last seven consecutive day period. Cases falling to a 7-day average of ~7,100 so as to amount to a total of 50,000 total cases in a seven consecutive day period between now and 15 June would mean that the situation at some point in the late spring/early summer would have to have improved so much so as to be just **3.6% of the current case numbers** (50,000/1,400,000 * 100 = 3.6%). Another way to think of this is it would mean **cases have to fall by 96.4% from where they are now**. This seems unlikely to me, especially given the fact that herd immunity through vaccination+cases is unlikely to have been achieved until late summer/early fall [2].

Unfortunately I do not believe this is even a remote possibility. The U.S. has not seen case numbers this low since the very beginning of the pandemic. To not go over 50,000 cases over a 7 day period, there would be an average of only 7,142.857 cases per day. According to the WHO, or any site tracking COVID, there hasn't been a 7 day average that low since the week of 9 March (or earlier), and the lowest case rate the U.S. has seen since was still at around 20,000 per day. With the dramatic increase we are about to see, I am not sure we can even get back down to 20,000 a day by then without another shutdown, and that seems unlikely considering the backlash from the last shutdown. I do no believe there will be enough vaccines available to make a dent by then either. I read an article recently that compares the vaccine to a fire hose to stop the spread of the virus. A highly effective Vaccine is a very strong fire hose. However, with the extremely high case rate we are seeing, we are taking a strong fire hose to fight the country's worst forest fire ever by comparison. If we had lower case rates, meaning it was just a small fire to put out, it would be a lot easier to see cases go down by then. Before the vaccine can be effective, we would need enough doses to vaccinate the majority of the population at the same time, or we would need a lower case rate and a good rate of vaccinations in areas where the cases are most prevalent. If the time frame were longer, say 15 December, I would have more faith in the vaccine helping to get case numbers that far down. However, our lowest case rate over a 7 day period since 9 March occurred during the week of 25 May, with an average case rate of 20,205 cases per day. The U.S. was nowhere near the case rate it is at now when the downward curve began, since the highest weekly rate was 219,073 in April before going down. We are seeing that many cases per day right now. The average case rate per week since 2 November in the U.S. is 1,047,842 new cases, and this includes the week of 2 November, which had 684,493 new cases according to the WHO. Without that week, the U.S. averaged 1,138,679 new cases per week during the last four weeks, and last week was 1,251,632 new cases in 7 days. It takes weeks to get the case numbers down after a surge that is significantly smaller than what we are seeing now, so who knows how long the current surge will effect us. The worst two months are yet to come, and I do not see it improving so drastically after spring comes that we see case numbers drop to about a third of what they were at our lowest case rate since the beginning of the pandemic. I hope I am wrong, but the math doesn't add up in our favor.

I think that it is more likely than not. 50k cases/week or roughly 7k cases/day would imply that contagion has slowed to a trickle. This could either happen through herd immunity (through immunization or people already having had COVID-19) and through fast detection and isolation of those who are contagious. Using data from Stockholm, Sweden it seems that about 10% of those infected are detected, which would give that there are already 140 million infected in the US. On the other hand - with an estimated death rate of .6% the total number of infected would be 46 million. I think 46 million is more certain so let's estimate the number to a weighted average 1/3 - 2/3, giving 77 million in the beginning of December. This doubling to 154 million by the beginning of June is not unreasonable. Regarding vaccines - I haven't seen a lot of numbers for 2021, but this article https://www.businessinsider.com/when-can-i-get-a-coronavirus-vaccine-timeline-2020-11?r=US&IR=T, mentions 30 million vaccines/ month in the beginning of the year (unclear if this is doses which would imply that the number treatments is half). Let's assume 15 million per month every month including May, which is 75 million people having been vaccinated by June 1. This would mean that 154+75 = 229 million could be immune. Of course some people who have already had the disease will receive the vaccine lowering this number say to 154+37.5=191.5. According to Herd immunity is believed to be reached when 60-80% of the population is immune (https://www.cnbc.com/2020/08/13/the-death-toll-would-be-enormous-fauci-says-of-herd-immunity-to-coronavirus-in-the-us.html). 191.5 million is 58% of the US population so almost within the herd immunity range. However, Fauci has said that he thinks it is possible that an "overwhelming majority" of the US population could be vaccinated by the end of June 2021, https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/528247-fauci-says-us-could-have-heard-immunity-by-end-of-summer-2021. In addition to this faster and more widespread testing would make tracing and isolating new cases easier. The main risk in this is associated with the vaccination program - failure in distribution, failure in uptake in general population and failure in the safety or efficiency of the vaccine. The number 50k/ week is also so low that the situation could be under control overall, but with localized outbreaks. My estimate of the number of people already infected could also be off and contagion suppression measures in the beginning of next year could slow down the spread reducing the number of already infected.

The US needs a 96.3% decrease in positive cases per day within the next 7 months. The biggest decrease the US has currently seen is 40% between late July and early September. From 01 Feb 2020 to present (14 Oct) I took the total number of registered cases (8,100,000) in the us and divided it by the number of weeks since 01 Feb (34). This provides an average weekly total of 238,235 cases per week. This was divided by 7 for a daily total of 34,033 cases. In order to strike the range posed by this question, the US will need to cut the rate of infection by 80%, or one fifth of the average weekly infection rate since 01 Feb. Even with successful development and fielding of a vaccine, distribution, trust, and continued ineffective containment protocols would erode confidence in achieving 1/5th of current infection rates. a projection of 20% best reflects the chance we arrive at a 20% rate of infection below current trends.
